I wanted to share early findings from an analysis I've been running to identify potential self-payment transactions — cases where a PNC customer appears to be sending money to themselves or a closely related entity, based on name similarity between the sender and the counterparty.

Please see the attached outputs and let me know your thoughts.


─────────────────────────────
WHAT WE'RE LOOKING FOR
─────────────────────────────

A self-payment occurs when the name of the originating customer closely matches the name of the counterparty receiving the funds. This can indicate:

  • Internal cash movement between related legal entities
  • Potential structuring or layering behavior
  • Legitimate but noteworthy treasury operations (e.g. holding company → operating company)

We focused exclusively on outgoing Wire and ACH transactions, since those are the primary B2B rails where this pattern is meaningful.


─────────────────────────────
DATA SCOPE
─────────────────────────────

  • Source: Staging payment table (all rails, all directions)
  • Starting volume: ~8 billion rows
  • After filters: ~1.5 billion rows (outgoing Wire + ACH, B2B only)
    - Wire: ~9.4M rows | $951B total value
    - ACH: ~1.52B rows | $5.1T total value (ACH filtered to $50K+ per transaction to remove consumer bill-pay noise)


─────────────────────────────
METHODOLOGY
─────────────────────────────

Step 1 — Pre-filtering
  Removed known payment processors, payroll hubs, card networks, and consumer-facing counterparties (PayPal, Venmo, credit card companies, utilities, retail, etc.) that would never represent self-payments. Also removed PNC's own internal entities.

Step 2 — Name normalization
  Standardized both customer name and counterparty name:
    • Lowercase
    • Strip punctuation (periods, commas, slashes)
    • Remove legal suffixes (INC, LLC, CORP, LP, etc.)
    • Collapse whitespace
  This allows "CASH MANAGEMENT SERVICES INC" and "Cash Management Services Inc." to be treated as the same entity.

Step 3 — Three-tier matching

  TIER 1 — Exact match after normalization: 1,304,593 transactions
    Highest confidence. Customer name and counterparty name are identical once normalized.
    Example: "CASH MANAGEMENT SERVICES INC" → "Cash Management Services Inc."

  TIER 1B — Same core name, different legal suffix: 547,256 transactions
    Same entity name but different legal wrapper (INC vs CO, INC vs blank, etc.).
    These may represent legitimate holding/operating company structures and warrant review.
    Example: "PROGRESSIVE CASUALTY INSURANCE CO" → "PROGRESSIVE CASUALTY INSURANCE"

  TIER 2 — Fuzzy match (Jaro-Winkler similarity ≥ 0.88): [see attached]
    Catches name abbreviations, word drops, and minor variations.
    201,367 distinct name pairs were scored. Pairs above the threshold are flagged.
    Example: "HIGHMARK WESTERN AND NORTHEASTERN NEW YORK INC" → "HIGHMARK"

Step 4 — Special pattern flag
  Transactions at or near $999,999,999 were separately flagged as likely system-capped settlement flows (a known pattern where a fund administrator hits a per-transaction system limit and splits a large transfer into max-amount chunks). These are likely legitimate but worth confirming.


─────────────────────────────
EARLY OBSERVATIONS
─────────────────────────────

  • The highest-value exact matches are large Wire transactions — Penn Mutual Life Insurance ($2.4B), Cash Management Services ($1.8B+), Transdigm ($1.1B). These appear to be internal treasury transfers between related legal entities rather than suspicious activity, but should be confirmed.

  • Dayforce Employer Funds Trust paying itself exactly $999,999,999 repeatedly is a clear settlement cap pattern — not suspicious, but notable.

  • The Tier 1B (suffix variant) set contains many large insurers and financial institutions — Progressive Casualty, Highmark, Salesforce, United States Life Insurance. These likely reflect legitimate multi-entity corporate structures.


